:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/F041632/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>Cicek's project addresses childhood as a social construction in the Muslim Turkish society of the Ottoman Empire and the early Turkish Republic in the nineteenth and early twentieth centuries. Cicek asserts that despite frequent assumptions to the contrary the &amp;quot;concept of childhood&amp;quot;, or an awareness of the particular nature of childhood, has existed in each age and society including pre-modern, non-Western societies like the Ottoman and Turkish one.&amp;nbsp; With a view to grasping the conception of childhood in the Ottoman-Turkish case, Cicek's project examines the &amp;quot;modern conception of childhood&amp;quot; as it emerged in the West where childhood was an ontology in its own right and where an Apollonian image of children as angelic creatures who have a natural goodness that can be idealised as the source of all that is best in human nature.&amp;nbsp; Drawing on sources such as magazines and journals aimed at children, parents and childcare professionals, popular books on pedagogy pediatrics and childrearing as well as biographical literature, Cicek elucidates the features of the &amp;quot;conception of childhood&amp;quot; as it emerged in Muslim Turkish society and demonstrates how the modernizing/Westernizing elites dramatically changed the ways that Muslim Turkish children were perceived, valued and treated in society.
